'''Cluj-Napoca''' ({{IPA-ro|<U+02C8>klu<U+0292> na<U+02C8>poka|-|Cluj-napoca.ogg}}; {{lang-de|Klausenburg}}; {{lang-hu|Kolozsv<U+00E1>r}}, {{IPA-hu|<U+02C8>kolo<U+0292>va<U+02D0>r|AUD|Kolozsv<U+00E1>r.ogg}}; [[Medieval Latin]]:  ''Castrum Clus'', ''Claudiopolis''; {{lang-yi|<U+05E7><U+05DC><U+05D5><U+05D9><U+05D6><U+05E0><U+05D1><U+05D5><U+05E8><U+05D2>}}, ''Kloiznburg''), commonly known as '''Cluj''', is the second most populous city in [[Romania]],<ref name="hotnews-6feb2012">{{cite web | url = http://www.hotnews.ro/stiri-esential-11436960-harta-interactiva-cum-schimbat-ierarhia-marilor-orase-din-tara-mai-ramas-doar-doua-orase-provincie-populatia-peste-300-000-locuitori.htm | title =Cum s-a schimbat ierarhia marilor ora<U+015F>e din <U+0163>ar<U+0103>. Au mai r<U+0103>mas doar dou<U+0103> ora<U+015F>e de provincie cu popula<U+0163>ia de peste 300.000 de locuitori | date =2012-02-06 | accessdate = 2012-02-14 | publisher = ''Hotnews.ro'' | language = Romanian}}</ref> behind the national capital [[Bucharest]], and is the seat of [[Cluj County]] in the northwestern part of the country. Geographically, it is roughly equidistant from Bucharest (324&nbsp;km / 201&nbsp;mi), [[Budapest]] (351&nbsp;km / 218&nbsp;mi) and [[Belgrade]] (322&nbsp;km / 200&nbsp;mi). Located in the [[Some<U+015F>ul Mic River]] valley, the city is considered the unofficial capital to the [[Historical regions of Romania|historical province]] of [[Transylvania]].  Between 1790 and 1848 and between 1861 and 1867, it was the official capital of the [[Grand Principality of Transylvania]].

As of 2011, 309,136 inhabitants live within the city limits, marking a decrease from the figure recorded at the 2002 census.<ref name="INSSE-Cluj-2011"/><ref name="population-2002">{{cite web|url=http://recensamant.referinte.transindex.ro/?pg=3&id=819|title=Municipiul Cluj-Napoca (data based on the 2002 census)|accessdate=2008-03-12|publisher=Funda<U+0163>ia Jakabffy Elem<U+00E9>r|language=Romanian}}</ref> The [[Cluj-Napoca metropolitan area]] has a population of 392,562 people,<ref name="INSSE-Cluj-2011"/><ref name="metro">{{cite web | url = http://www.cjcluj.ro/zona-metropolitana-urbana/ | title = Zona Metropolitana Urbana | accessdate = May 25, 2009 | publisher = CJ Cluj | language = Romanian}}</ref> while the population of the [[wikt:peri-urban|peri-urban]] area (Romanian: ''zona periurban<U+0103>'') exceeds 400,000 residents.<ref name="INSSE-Cluj-2011"/><ref name="periurban">{{cite web
|url=http://www.cjcluj.ro/zona-metropolitana-urbana/|title=Zona Metropolitan<U+0103> Urban<U+0103> <U+015F>i Strategii de Dezvoltare a Zonei Metropolitane Cluj-Napoca|accessdate=2008-03-12|publisher=Cluj County Council|language=Romanian}}</ref> The new metropolitan government of Cluj-Napoca became operational in December 2008.<ref name="ziua-metropola">{{cite web|url=http://www.ziuadecj.ro/action/article?ID=20381|title=Asocia<U+0163>ia Metropolitan<U+0103> e "la cheie". Mai trebuie banii|date=2009-01-09|accessdate=2009-02-11|publisher=Ziua de Cluj|language=Romanian}}</ref> Lastly, according to the 2007 data provided by the County Population Register Service, the total population of the city is as high as 392,276 people.<ref name="flotanti">{{cite web
|url=http://www.ftr.ro/wanted-clujeanul-verde-2898.php|title=Wanted: clujeanul verde|date=2008-03-06|accessdate=2008-05-12|publisher=Foaia Transilvan<U+0103>|language=Romanian}}</ref> However, this number does not include the floating population of students and other non-residents<U+2014>an average of over 20,000 people each year during 2004&ndash;2007, according to the same source.<ref name="flotanti"/>

The city spreads out from [[St. Michael's Church, Cluj-Napoca|St. Michael's Church]] in [[Unirii Square, Cluj-Napoca|Unirii Square]], built in the 14th century and named after [[Michael (archangel)|the Archangel Michael]], the [[patron saint]] of Cluj-Napoca.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clujonline.com/ro/catedrala_sf_mihail.htm|title=Catedrala "Sf. Mihail"|accessdate=2008-03-12|publisher=Clujonline.com|language=Romanian}}</ref> The boundaries of the municipality contain an area of {{convert|179.52|km2|sqmi}}. An analysis undertaken by the real estate agency Profesional Casa indicates that, because of infrastructure development, [[Communes of Romania|communes]] such as Feleacu, V<U+00E2>lcele, M<U+0103>rtine<U+015F>ti, Jucu and Baciu will eventually become neighbourhoods of the city, thereby enlarging its area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ziuadecj.ro/action/article;jsessionid=F9FA41C0734C312C8327DDCC67723E9A?ID=4488|title=Comunele din jurul Clujului se transform<U+0103> <U+00EE>n cartiere|date=2007-10-29|accessdate=2008-03-12|publisher=Ziua de Cluj|language=Romanian |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080321124000/http://www.ziuadecj.ro/action/article;jsessionid=F9FA41C0734C312C8327DDCC67723E9A?ID=4488 |archivedate = March 21, 2008}}</ref>

Cluj-Napoca experienced a decade of decline during the 1990s, its international reputation suffering from the policies of its mayor of the time, [[Gheorghe Funar]].<ref name="ftimes">{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/97363fb4-ea07-11dc-b3c9-0000779fd2ac.html|title=Cluj: Buzz grips university town|date=2008-03-06|accessdate=2008-03-13|publisher=Financial Times}}</ref> Today, the city is one of the most important academic, cultural, industrial and business centres in Romania. Among other institutions, it hosts the country's largest university, [[Babe<U+015F>-Bolyai University]], with its famous [[Cluj-Napoca Botanical Garden|botanical garden]]; nationally renowned cultural institutions; as well as the largest Romanian-owned commercial bank.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.monocle.com/sections/affairs/Magazine-Articles/Five-alive--New-regions/|title=Five alive - New regions - Five territories to watch|date=Issue 09, Volume 01, December 2007|accessdate=2008-03-12|publisher=Monocle}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clujeanul.ro/cluj/presa-britanica-clujul-campion-mondial-la-dezvoltare-2327155|author=Alexandra Groza|title=Presa britanic<U+0103>: "Clujul, campion mondial la dezvoltare"|date=2008-01-08|accessdate=2008-03-12|publisher=Clujeanul|language=Romanian}}</ref> According to the American magazine ''[[InformationWeek]]'', Cluj-Napoca is quickly becoming Romania's technopolis.<ref name="technopolis">{{cite web|url=http://www.informationweek.com/showArticle.jhtml;jsessionid=WRL0GCTCWCB2AQSNDLPCKHSCJUNN2JVN?articleID=206103523&queryText=cluj|title=Romania Proving Popular As Software Outsourcing Destination|date=2008-02-04|accessdate=2008-03-12|publisher=InformationWeek}}</ref>

== Etymology ==
[[File:Tiperit en Klus.JPG|thumb|left|Romanian inscription of a religious book: "Tiperit en Klus en Anul Domnului 1703" (Printed in Klus AD 1703).]]

On the site of the city was a pre-Roman settlement named Napoca. After the AD 106 [[Roman Empire|Roman]] conquest of the area, the place was known as ''Municipium Aelium Hadrianum Napoca''. Possible etymologies for ''Napoca'' or ''Napuca'' include the names of some [[Dacia]]n tribes such as the Naparis or Napaei, the Greek term ''napos'' (<U+03BD><U+03AC><U+03C0><U+03BF><U+03C2>), meaning "timbered valley" or the Indo-European root ''*sn<U+0101>-p-'' ([[Indogermanisches etymologisches W<U+00F6>rterbuch|Pokorny]] 971-2), "to flow, to swim, damp".<ref name="etim-napoca">Luk<U+00E1>cs 2005, p.14</ref>

The first written mention of the city's current name <U+2013> as a Royal Borough <U+2013> was in 1213 under the Latin name ''[[Castrum]] Clus''.<ref name="sasi">{{cite web|url=http://clujnet.com/romana/001_cluj_napoca/istorie/03-colonistii_sasi.htm|title=O istorie inedit<U+0103> a Clujului - Cetatea coloni<U+015F>tilor sa<U+015F>i|publisher=ClujNet.com|accessdate=2008-03-16|language=Romanian|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080130171551/http://clujnet.com/romana/001_cluj_napoca/istorie/03-colonistii_sasi.htm |archivedate = January 30, 2008|deadurl=yes}}</ref> Despite the fact that ''Clus'' as a county name was recorded in the 1173 document ''Thomas comes Clusiensis'',<ref name="medieval">Lazarovici et al. 1997, p.32 (3.1 De la Napoca roman<U+0103> la Clujul medieval)</ref> it is believed that the county's designation derives from the name of the ''castrum'', which might have existed prior to its first mention in 1213, and not vice versa.<ref name="medieval"/> With respect to the name of this camp, it is widely accepted as a derivation from the Latin term ''clausa&nbsp;<U+2013>&nbsp;clusa'', meaning "closed place", "strait", "ravine".<ref name="medieval"/> Similar senses are attributed to the Slavic term ''klu<U+010D>'', meaning "a [[Cay|key]]"<ref name="medieval"/> and the German ''Klause&nbsp;<U+2013>&nbsp;Kluse'' (meaning mountain pass or weir).<ref name="szabadsag1">{{cite web|url=http://www.szabadsag.ro/archivum/2000/0sep-19.htm|last=Gaal|first=Gy<U+00F6>rgy|title=Kolozsv<U+00E1>ri kronol<U+00F3>gia - Kolozsv<U+00E1>r k<U+00E9>tezer esztendeje d<U+00E1>tumokban|publisher=Szabads<U+00E1>g|date=2000-07-19|accessdate=2008-03-15|language=Hungarian}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> The Latin and Slavic names have been attributed to the valley that narrows or closes between hills just to the west of [[M<U+0103>n<U+0103><U+015F>tur|Cluj-M<U+0103>n<U+0103><U+015F>tur]].<ref name="medieval"/> An alternative hypothesis relates the name of the city to its first magistrate, Miklus&nbsp;<U+2013>&nbsp;Mikl<U+00F3>s / Kolos.<ref name="szabadsag1"/>

The Hungarian form, first recorded in 1246 as ''Kulusuar'', underwent various phonetic changes over the years (''uar''/''v<U+00E1>r'' means "castle" in Hungarian); the variant ''Koloswar'' first appears in a document from 1332.<ref name="szabadsag2">{{cite web|url=http://www.szabadsag.ro/archivum/2003/08/3aug-04.htm|last=Asztalos|first=Lajos|title=Kolozsv<U+00E1>r neve|publisher=Szabads<U+00E1>g|date=2003-08-04|accessdate=2008-03-15|language=Hungarian}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> Its Saxon name ''Clusenburg''/''Clusenbvrg'' appeared in 1348, but from 1408 the form Clausenburg was used.<ref name="szabadsag2"/> The Romanian name of the city used to be spelled alternately as ''Cluj'' or ''Clu<U+015F>'',<ref name="etim-dict">{{cite web|url=http://dictionar.referinte.transindex.ro/index.php3?action=betu&betu=k&kezd=60&co=nemet|title=Dic<U+0163>ionar de localit<U+0103><U+0163>i din Transilvania|last=Szab<U+00F3>|first=Attila m.|accessdate=2008-03-15|language=Romanian}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> the latter being the case in [[Mihai Eminescu]]'s ''Poesis''. In 1974, the [[Communist Romania|Romanian Communist authorities]] added "-Napoca" back to the city's name as a nationalist gesture, emphasising its pre-Roman roots.<ref>{{cite book|last=Herb|first=Guntram Henrik|authorlink=|coauthors=David H. Kaplan|editor=|others=George W. White|title=Nested Identities: Nationalism, Territory, and Scale|origdate=|origyear=|origmonth=|url=http://books.google.com/?id=ikVCJQIJsNoC&pg=PA267&dq=John+Hunyadi+Transylvania|accessdate=2008-05-26|edition=|series=|volume=|year=1999|month=|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|location=|language=|isbn=0-8476-8467-9|oclc=|doi=|id=|page=275|chapter=Transylvania:Hungarian, Romanian, or Neither?|chapterurl=|quote=}}</ref><ref name="name-1974">{{cite web|url=http://www.clujonline.com/ro/istoric.htm|title=Cluj-Napoca. Istoric|publisher=Clujonline.com|accessdate=2008-03-14|language=Romanian}}</ref> The full name is rarely used outside of official contexts.<ref>Brubaker et al. 2006, p.xxi</ref> In [[Yiddish language|Yiddish]] it is known as ''{{lang|yi|<U+05E7><U+05DC><U+05D0><U+05D6><U+05D9><U+05DF>}}'' (''Klazin'') or ''{{lang|yi|<U+05E7><U+05DC><U+05D5><U+05D9><U+05D6><U+05E2><U+05E0><U+05D1><U+05D5><U+05E8><U+05D2>}}'' (Kloyznburg).<ref name="etim-dict"/>

== History ==
{{Main|History of Cluj-Napoca}}

===Roman Empire===
[[File:Part of Tabula Peutingeriana centered around present day Transylvania.png|thumb|text-top|upright=1.5|Napoca on the [[Roman Dacia]] fragment of the 1st-4th century AD [[Tabula Peutingeriana]] (upper center){{sfn|Bunbury|1879|p=516}}]]
The [[Roman Empire]] conquered [[Dacia]] in AD 101 and 106, during the rule of [[Trajan]], and the Roman settlement Napoca, established thereafter, is first recorded on a milestone discovered in 1758 in the vicinity of the city.<ref name="roman">Lazarovici ''et. al.'' 1997, pp. 202-3 (6.2 Cluj in the Old and Ancient Epochs)</ref> Trajan's successor [[Hadrian]] granted Napoca the status of ''[[municipium]]'' as ''municipium Aelium Hadrianum Napocenses''. Later, in the 2nd century AD,<ref>Lazarovici et al. 1997, p. 17 (2.7 Napoca roman<U+0103>)</ref> the city gained the status of a ''[[colonia (Roman)|colonia]]'' as ''Colonia Aurelia Napoca''. Napoca became a provincial capital of [[Dacia Porolissensis]] and thus the seat of a [[promagistrate|procurator]]. The ''colonia'' was evacuated in 274 by the Romans.<ref name="roman"/> There are no references to urban settlement on the site for the better part of a millennium thereafter.<ref>Brubaker et al. 2006, p.89</ref>

===Middle Ages===
[[File:Claudiopolis.jpg|thumb|left|''"Claudiopolis, Coloswar vulgo Clausenburg, Transilvani<U+00E6> civitas primaria"''. Gravure{{ref label|a|a|none}} of medieval Cluj by Georg Houfnagel (1617)]]
At the beginning of the [[Middle Ages]], two groups of buildings existed on the current site of the city: the wooden fortress at [[M<U+0103>n<U+0103><U+015F>tur|Cluj-M<U+0103>n<U+0103><U+015F>tur]] (''Kolozsmonostor'') and the civilian settlement developed around the current ''Pia<U+0163>a Muzeului'' (Museum Place) in the city centre.<ref name="medieval"/><ref name="alicu">Alicu 2003, p.9</ref> Although the precise date of the conquest of Transylvania by the [[Hungarian people|Hungarians]] is not known, the earliest Hungarian artifacts found in the region are dated to the first half of the 10th century.<ref>{{cite book|last=Madgearu|first=Alexandru|title=Rom<U+00E2>nii <U+00EE>n opera Notarului Anonim|year=2001|isbn=973-577-249-3|publisher=Centrul de Studii Transilvane, Funda<U+021B>ia Cultural<U+0103> Rom<U+00E2>n<U+0103>|location=Cluj-Napoca}}</ref> In any case, after that time, the city became part of the [[Kingdom of Hungary]]. King [[Stephen I of Hungary|Stephen I]] made the city the seat of the castle county of Kolozs, and King Saint [[Ladislaus I of Hungary]] founded the abbey of Cluj-M<U+0103>n<U+0103><U+015F>tur (''Kolozsmonostor''), destroyed during the [[Tatar]] invasions in 1241 and 1285.<ref name="medieval"/> As for the civilian colony, a castle and a village were built to the northwest of the ancient Napoca no later than the late 12th century.<ref name="medieval"/> This new village was settled by large groups of [[Transylvanian Saxons]], encouraged during the reign of Crown Prince [[Stephen V of Hungary|Stephen]], Duke of Transylvania.<ref name="sasi"/> The first reliable mention of the settlement dates from 1275, in a document of King [[Ladislaus IV of Hungary]], when the village (''Villa Kulusvar'') was granted to the Bishop of Transylvania.<ref name="first-mention">Lazarovici et al. 1997, p. 204 (6.3 Medieval Cluj)</ref> On August 19, 1316, during the rule of the new king, [[Charles I of Hungary]], Cluj was granted the status of a city ([[Latin language|Latin]]: ''civitas''), as a reward for the Saxons' contribution to the defeat of the rebellious Transylvanian [[voivode]], [[Ladislaus K<U+00E1>n]].<ref name="first-mention"/>

[[File:Palatul de Justi<U+0163>ie din Cluj-Napoca.jpg|thumb|The [[Palace of Justice, Cluj-Napoca|Palace of Justice]]]]
Many craft guilds were established in the second half of the 13th century, and a patrician stratum based in commerce and craft production displaced the older landed elite in the town's leadership.<ref>Brubaker et al. 2006, pp.89-90</ref> Through the privilege granted by [[Sigismund, Holy Roman Emperor|Sigismund of Luxembourg]] in 1405, the city opted out from the jurisdiction of voivodes, vice-voivodes and royal judges, and obtained the right to elect a twelve-member jury every year.<ref name="free-city">Lazarovici et al. 1997, p.38 (3.1 De la Napoca roman<U+0103> la Clujul medieval)</ref> In 1488, King [[Matthias Corvinus of Hungary|Matthias Corvinus]] (born in Klausenburg in 1440) ordered that the centumvirate<U+2014>the city council, consisting of one hundred men<U+2014>be half composed from the ''homines bone conditiones'' (the wealthy people), with craftsmen supplying the other half; together they would elect the chief judge and the jury.<ref name="free-city"/> Meanwhile, an agreement was reached providing that half of the representatives on this city council were to be drawn from the Hungarian, half from the Saxon population, and that judicial offices were to be held on a rotating basis.<ref name="centumvirate">Brubaker et al. 2006, pp. 90-1</ref> In 1541, Klausenburg became part of the independent Principality of Transylvania after the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman Turks]] occupied the central part of the Kingdom of Hungary; a period of economic and cultural prosperity followed.<ref name="centumvirate"/> Although [[Alba Iulia]] (''Gyulafeh<U+00E9>rv<U+00E1>r'') served as a political capital for the princes of Transylvania, Klausenburg enjoyed the support of the princes to a greater extent, thus establishing connections with the most important centres of Eastern Europe at that time, along with [[Ko<U+0161>ice]] (''Kassa''), [[Krak<U+00F3>w]], Prague and Vienna.<ref name="free-city"/>

===16th<U+2013>18th centuries===
In terms of religion, [[Protestant Reformation|Protestant]] ideas first appeared in the middle of the 16th century. During [[G<U+00E1>sp<U+00E1>r Heltai]]'s service as preacher, [[Lutheranism]] grew in importance, as did the Swiss doctrine of [[Calvinism]].<ref name="religion-history">Lazarovici et al. 1997, p. 205 (6.3 Medieval Cluj)</ref> By 1571, the [[Turda]] (''Torda'') Diet had adopted a more radical religion, [[Ferenc D<U+00E1>vid]]'s [[Unitarianism]], characterised by the free interpretation of the Bible and denial of the dogma of the [[Trinity]].<ref name="religion-history"/> [[Stephen B<U+00E1>thory of Poland|Stephen B<U+00E1>thory]] founded a Catholic [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]] academy in Klausenburg in order to promote an anti-Reform movement; however, it did not have much success.<ref name="religion-history"/> For a year, in 1600<U+2013>1601, Cluj became part of the [[personal union]] of [[Michael the Brave]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Cristina|last=Mart<U+00E2>niuc|url=http://www.cnaa.acad.md/files/theses/2007/5770/cristina_martiniuc_thesis.pdf|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20070108120718/http://www.cnaa.acad.md/files/theses/2007/5770/cristina_martiniuc_thesis.pdf|archivedate=2007-01-08|title=Probleme actuale ale calit<U+0103><U+0163>ii de subiect de drept interna<U+0163>ional public contemporan|publisher=CNAA (Republic of Moldova)|accessdate=2008-03-17|language=Romanian|quote=<U+00CE>n istoria poporului rom<U+00E2>n, o uniune personal<U+0103> a fost creat<U+0103> <U+00EE>n anul 1600 prin unirea politic<U+0103> a celor trei <U+0163><U+0103>ri Rom<U+00E2>ne<U+015F>ti <U+2013> Transilvania, Moldova <U+015F>i <U+0162>ara Rom<U+00E2>neasc<U+0103> <U+2013> sub un singur domnitor: Mihai Vod<U+0103> Viteazul (In the history of the Romanian people, a personal union was created in 1600 with the political union of the three Romanian countries - Transylvania, Moldova and Wallachia - under a single ruler: Michael the Brave)|format=PDF}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first=George|last=Cior<U+0103>nescu|title=Michael the Brave - Evaluations and Revaluations of the Walachian Prince|publisher=Radio Free Europe Research: RAD Background Report/191|date=1976-09-01|accessdate=2008-03-15|url=http://www.osa.ceu.hu/files/holdings/300/8/3/pdf/52-4-102.pdf|format=PDF|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080408202135/http://www.osa.ceu.hu/files/holdings/300/8/3/pdf/52-4-102.pdf |archivedate = April 8, 2008|deadurl=yes}}</ref> Under the [[Treaty of Carlowitz]] in 1699, Klausenburg became part of the [[Habsburg Monarchy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/eb/article-9020364/Treaty-of-Carlowitz|title=Treaty of Carlowitz|publisher=Encyclop<U+00E6>dia Britannica|year=2008|accessdate=2008-03-14}}</ref>

[[File:Kolozsv<U+00E1>r New York-palota.jpg|thumb|The New York Palace]]
In the 17th century, Cluj suffered from great calamities, suffering from epidemics of the [[Plague (disease)|plague]] and devastating fires.<ref name="religion-history"/> The end of this century brought the end of Turkish sovereignty, but found the city bereft of much of its wealth, municipal freedom, cultural centrality, political significance and even population.<ref name="17th-century">Brubaker et al. 2006, p.91</ref> It gradually regained its important position within Transylvania as the headquarters of the Gubernium and the Diets between 1719 and 1732, and again from 1790 until the [[Hungarian Revolution of 1848|revolution of 1848]], when the Gubernium moved to [[Sibiu|Hermannstadt]] (now Sibiu).<ref name="capital-trans">Lazarovici et al. 1997, pp.42,44,68 (3.1 De la Napoca roman<U+0103> la Clujul medieval; 4.1 Centru al mi<U+015F>c<U+0103>rii na<U+0163>ionale)</ref> In 1791, a group of [[Romanians|Romanian]] intellectuals drew up a petition, known as ''[[Supplex Libellus Valachorum]]'', which was sent to the Emperor in Vienna. The petition demanded the equality of the Romanian nation in Transylvania in respect to the other nations (Saxon and Hungarian) governed by the ''[[Unio Trium Nationum]]'', but it was rejected by the Cluj Diet.<ref name="religion-history"/>

===19th century===
Beginning in 1830, the city became the centre of the Hungarian national movement within the principality.<ref name="national-move">Lazarovici et al. 1997, p.206 (6.4 Cluj in Modern Times)</ref> This erupted with the [[Hungarian Revolution of 1848]].  At one point, the Austrians were gaining control of Transylvania, trapping the Hungarians between two flanks. But, the Hungarian army, headed by the [[Poles|Polish]] general [[J<U+00F3>zef Bem]], launched an offensive in Transylvania, recapturing Klausenburg by Christmas 1848.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mek.oszk.hu/03400/03407/html/370.html|title=Bem's Campaign in Transylvania; Revolutionary Consolidation and Its Contradictions|publisher=MEK (Hungarian Electronic Library)|accessdate=2008-03-14}}</ref> After the 1848 revolution, an [[Absolutism (European history)|absolutist]] regime was established, followed by a liberal regime that came to power in 1860. In this latter period, the government granted equal rights to the ethnic Romanians, but only briefly.  In 1865, the Diet in Cluj abolished the laws voted in Sibiu, and proclaimed the 1848 Law concerning the Union of Transylvania with Hungary.<ref name="national-move"/> Before 1918, the city's only Romanian-language schools were two church-run elementary schools, and the first printed Romanian periodical did not appear until 1903.<ref name="17th-century"/>

[[File:Josephinische Landaufnahme pg083.jpg|left|Cluj-Napoca in the Grand Duchy of Transylvania maps, 1769&ndash;1773. Josephinische Landesaufnahme|300px|thumb]]
After the [[Austro-Hungarian Compromise of 1867]], Klausenburg and all of Transylvania were again integrated into the Kingdom of Hungary. During this time, Kolozsv<U+00E1>r was among the largest and most important cities of the kingdom and was the seat of [[Kolozs]] County. Ethnic Romanians in Transylvania suffered oppression and persecution.<ref name="memorandum">Lazarovici et al. 1997, pp.74-5 (6.4 Centru al mi<U+015F>c<U+0103>rii na<U+0163>ionale)</ref> Their grievances found expression in the [[Transylvanian Memorandum]], a petition sent in 1892 by the political leaders of Transylvania's Romanians to the Austro-Hungarian [[Kaiserlich und k<U+00F6>niglich|Emperor-King]] [[Franz Joseph I of Austria|Franz Joseph]]. It asked for equal rights with the Hungarians and demanded an end to persecutions and attempts at [[Magyarisation]].<ref name="memorandum"/> The Emperor forwarded the memorandum to Budapest<U+2014>the Hungarian capital.  The authors, among them [[Ioan Ra<U+0163>iu]] and Iuliu Coroianu, were arrested, tried and sentenced to prison for "high treason" in Kolozsv<U+00E1>r/Cluj in May 1894.<ref name="elite-popor">{{cite web|url=http://www.edrc.ro/docs/docs/transilvania/198-254.pdf|title=Rela<U+0163>ia dintre elite <U+015F>i popor <U+00EE>n perioada memorandist<U+0103>|publisher=Centrul de Resurse pentru Diversitate Etnocultural<U+0103>|location=Cluj|accessdate=2008-03-15|language=Romanian|format=PDF}}</ref> During the trial, approximately 20,000 people who had come to Cluj demonstrated on the streets of the city in support of the defendants.<ref name="elite-popor"/> A year later, the King gave them pardon upon the advice of his Hungarian prime minister, [[Dezs<U+0151> B<U+00E1>nffy]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Ambrus Miskolczy|url=http://adatbank.transindex.ro/html/alcim_pdf2813.pdf|title=A modern rom<U+00E1>n nemzet a "r<U+00E9>gi" Magyarorsz<U+00E1>gon|year=2001|accessdate=2010-07-29|publisher=Rubicon|language=Hungarian}}</ref> In 1897, the Hungarian government decided that only Hungarian place names should be used and prohibited the use of the German or Romanian versions of the city's name on official government documents.<ref name="castellan89">{{cite book|author=Georges Castellan|title=A history of the Romanians|publisher=Boulder: East European Monographs|year=1989|page=148|isbn=978-0-88033-154-8}}</ref>

===20th century===
[[File:Kv<U+00E1>r Neol<U+00F3>g zsinag<U+00F3>ga.jpg|thumb|[[Cluj-Napoca Reformed Synagogue]]]]
[[Image:Cluj la 1930, Vedere Aeriana.jpg|thumb|right|220px|Central Cluj-Napoca in 1930]]
In the autumn of 1918, as World War I drew to a close, Cluj became a centre of revolutionary activity, headed by [[Amos Fr<U+00E2>ncu]].  On October 28, 1918, he made an appeal for the organisation of the "union of all Romanians".<ref name="laz-union">Lazarovici ''et. al.'' 1997, p. 207 (6.4 Cluj in Modern Times)</ref> Thirty-nine delegates were elected from Cluj to attend the proclamation of the [[Union of Transylvania with Romania|union of Transylvania with the Kingdom of Romania]] in [[Alba-Iulia]] on December 1, 1918,<ref name="laz-union"/> later acknowledged internationally by the [[Treaty of Trianon]].<ref>Ernest A. Rockwell: Trianon Politics, 1994&ndash;1995, thesis, Central Missouri State University, 1995</ref> The [[Interwar period|interwar years]] saw the new authorities embark on a "Romanianisation" campaign: a [[Capitoline Wolf Statue, Cluj-Napoca|Capitoline Wolf statue]] donated by Rome was set up in 1921; in 1932 a plaque written by historian [[Nicolae Iorga]] was placed on Matthias Corvinus' statue, emphasising his Romanian (paternal) ancestry; and construction of an imposing [[Orthodox Christianity|Orthodox]] cathedral began in a city where only about a tenth of inhabitants belonged to the Orthodox state church.<ref name="brubaker-interwar">Brubaker et al. 2006, pp. 100-1</ref> This endeavour had only mixed results: by 1939, Hungarians still dominated local economic (and to a certain extent) cultural life: for instance, Cluj had five Hungarian daily newspapers and just one in Romanian.<ref name="brubaker-interwar"/>

In 1940, Cluj, along with the rest of [[Northern Transylvania]], became part of [[Mikl<U+00F3>s Horthy]]'s Hungary through the [[Second Vienna Award]] imposed by [[Nazi Germany]] and [[Kingdom of Italy (1861<U+2013>1946)|Fascist Italy]].<ref>{{cite book|first=Dennis P.|last=Hupchick|title=Conflict and Chaos in Eastern Europe|location=London|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|year=1995|page=91|isbn=0-312-12116-4}}</ref><ref name="ww2"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F30811FC3454107A93C0A81782D85F448485F9&scp=3&sq=cluj&st=p|title=Hungarians' Army Marches into Cluj; Receives a Frenzied Welcome From Magyars in Former Rumanian Territory But Atmosphere Is Tense Officers of Occupying Troops Charge That 12 Were Slain by Retreating Force|work=The New York Times|date=1940-07-12|accessdate=2008-03-15 | first=C.L. | last=Sulzberger}}</ref> After the Germans occupied Hungary in March 1944 and installed a puppet government under [[D<U+00F6>me Szt<U+00F3>jay]],<ref>{{cite book|author=Peter Kenez|url=http://assets.cambridge.org/052185/766X/excerpt/052185766X_excerpt.htm|title=Hungary from the Nazis to the Soviets - the establishment of the Communist regime in Hungary, 1944&ndash;1948|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=0-521-85766-X|month=May|year=2006|accessdate=2008-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first=Richard J.|last=Evans|title=Lying About Hitler: History, Holocaust, and the David Irving Trial|location=London|publisher=Basic Books|year=2001|page=95|isbn=0-465-02153-0}}</ref> they forced large-scale [[Antisemitism|antisemitic]] measures in the city. The headquarters of the local [[Gestapo]] were located in the New York Hotel. That May, the authorities began the relocation of the Jews to the [[Cluj-Napoca Iris Ghetto|Iris ghetto]].<ref name="ww2">Lazarovici et al. 1997, pp. 140-1 (5.2 Dictatul de la Viena - 30 august 1940)</ref> Liquidation of the 16,148 captured Jews occurred through six deportations to [[Auschwitz]] in May<U+2013>June 1944.<ref name="ww2"/> Despite facing severe sanctions from the Hungarian administration, some Jews escaped across the border to Romania with the assistance of intellectuals such as [[Emil Ha<U+0163>ieganu]], [[Raoul <U+015E>orban]], Aurel Socol and Miskolczy Dezs<U+0151>, and various peasants from M<U+0103>n<U+0103><U+015F>tur.<ref name="ww2"/>

On October 11, 1944 the city was captured by [[Romanian Army|Romanian]] and [[Red Army|Soviet]] troops.<ref name="ww2"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F50910FF3555157B93C0A8178BD95F408485F9&scp=2&sq=cluj&st=p|title=Russians Smash on; Memel Reported Cut Off as New Drive Reaches German Frontier Szeged, Cluj Seized Soviet Tanks Cross Tisza, Menacing Budapest, Berlin Admits Russians Smash on Near East Prussia|work=The New York Times|date=1944-10-12|accessdate=2008-03-15}}</ref> It was formally restored to the [[Kingdom of Romania]] by the [[Paris Peace Treaties, 1947|Treaty of Paris]] in 1947. On January 24, March 6 and May 10, 1946, the Romanian students who had come back to Cluj after the restoration of northern Transylvania rose against the claims of autonomy made by nostalgic Hungarians and the new way of life imposed by the Soviets, resulting in clashes and street fights.<ref>Lazarovici et al. 1997, p. 213 (6.5 Cluj in Modern Times)</ref>[[File:Strada Regele Ferdinand.jpg|thumb|King Ferdinand Street]]

The [[Hungarian Revolution of 1956]] produced a powerful echo within the city; there was a real possibility that demonstrations by students sympathizing with their peers across the border could escalate into an uprising.<ref>Lazarovici et al. 1997, p. 153 (5.3 Perioada totalitarismului)</ref><ref>Johanna Granville, [http://www.scribd.com/doc/13734484/Romanian-Students-Reactions-to-the-Hungarian-Revolution-of-1956 "If Hope is Sin, Then We Are All Guilty: Romanian Students<U+2019> Reactions to the Hungarian Revolution and Soviet Intervention, 1956-1958]", ''Carl Beck Paper'', no. 1905 (April 2008): 1-78.</ref> The protests provided the Romanian authorities with a pretext to speed up the process of "unification" of the local Babe<U+015F> (Romanian) and Bolyai (Hungarian) universities,<ref>{{cite journal|first=Andrew|last=Ludanyi|journal=Hungarian Studies|format=PDF|title=The Impact of 1956 on the Hungarians of Transylvania|page=93|publisher=Akad<U+00E9>miai Kiad<U+00F3>|doi=10.1556/HStud.20.2006.1.9|volume=20|issue=1|month=June|year=2006|laydate=2007-05-08|url=http://www.akademiai.com/content/723n44tjh3455420/fulltext.pdf|accessdate=2008-03-21}}</ref> allegedly contemplated before the 1956 events.<ref>{{cite book|last=K<U+00E1>lm<U+00E1>n|first=Aniszi|title=A Bolyai Tudom<U+00E1>nyegyetem utols<U+00F3> esztendeje: Besz<U+00E9>lget<U+00E9>s dr. Sebesty<U+00E9>n K<U+00E1>lm<U+00E1>nnal|publisher=Hitel, XII, No. 3|month=March|year=1999|page=83}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=A rom<U+00E1>niai magyar f<U+00F5>iskolai oktat<U+00E1>s: M<U+00FA>lt, jelen, j<U+00F6>v<U+00F5>|location=Cluj/Kolozsv<U+00E1>r|publisher=Jelenl<U+00E9>t Alkot<U+00F3> T<U+00E1>rsas<U+00E1>g|year=1990|page=21}}</ref> Hungarians remained the majority of the city's population until the 1960s.  Then Romanians began to outnumber Hungarians,<ref name="varga-arpad">{{cite web|url=http://varga.adatbank.transindex.ro/?pg=3&action=etnik&id=5290|title=Erd<U+00E9>ly etnikai <U+00E9>s felekezeti statisztik<U+00E1>ja (1850&ndash;1992)|author=Varga E. <U+00C1>rp<U+00E1>d|accessdate=2008-03-16|language=Hungarian}}</ref> due to the population increase as a result of the government's forced industrialisation of the city and new jobs.<ref name=industrialisation>Lazarovici et al. 1997, pp. 154,159 (5.3 Perioada totalitarismului)</ref> During the [[Communist Romania|Communist period]], the city recorded a high industrial development, as well as enforced construction expansion.<ref name=industrialisation/> On October 16, 1974, when the city celebrated 1850 years since its first mention as Napoca, the [[Communist Romania|Communist government]] changed the name of the city by adding "Napoca" to it.<ref name="name-1974"/>

===Late 20th and early 21st century===
During the [[Romanian Revolution of 1989]], Cluj-Napoca was one of the scenes of the rebellion: 26 were killed and approximately 170 injured.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ceausescu.org/ceausescu_texts/revolution/catavencu.htm|title=O mur<U+0103> <U+00EE>n gura comisiei "Evenimentele din decembrie"|publisher=Academia Ca<U+0163>avencu|date=1996-01-30|accessdate =2008-03-21|language=Romanian}}</ref> After the end of totalitarian rule, the nationalist politician [[Gheorghe Funar]] became mayor and governed for the next 12&nbsp;years. His tenure was marked by strong Romanian nationalism and acts of [[ethnic]] provocation against the Hungarian-speaking minority. This deterred foreign investment;<ref name="ftimes"/> however, in [[Politics of Cluj-Napoca|June 2004]], Gheorghe Funar was voted out of office, and the city entered a period of rapid economic growth.<ref name="ftimes"/> From 2004 to 2009, the mayor was [[Emil Boc]], concurrently president of the [[Democratic Liberal Party (Romania)|Democratic Liberal Party]].  He went on to be elected as [[Prime Minister of Romania|prime minister]], returning as mayor in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cotidianul.ro/guvernul_boc_a_fost_investit_de_parlament-68423.html|title=Guvernul Boc a fost <U+00EE>nvestit de Parlament|publisher=Cotidianul|date=2008-12-22|accessdate=2009-07-22|language=Romanian}}</ref><ref name="juramant">{{cite web|url=http://www.adevarul.ro/locale/cluj-napoca/Emil_Boc_a_depus_juramantul_de_primar_0_723527938.html|title=Emil Boc a depus jur<U+0103>m<U+00E2>ntul de primar|author=Bianca Preda|publisher=Adev<U+0103>rul|date=2012-06-22|accessdate=2012-06-22|language=Romanian}}</ref>

== Geography ==
[[File:Casa Parcul Central Cluj-Napoca.jpg|thumb|left|[[Cluj-Napoca Central Park|Central Park]] residence]]
[[File:Banks Somes Cluj 1.jpg|thumb|The banks of the [[Some<U+015F>ul Mic River]]]]
[[File:Statuie Gradina Botanica Cluj-Napoca.jpg|thumb|The Roman garden within the local [[Cluj-Napoca Botanical Garden|botanical garden]]]]
Cluj-Napoca, located in the central part of [[Transylvania]], has a surface area of {{convert|179.5|km2|sqmi}}. The city lies at the confluence of the [[Apuseni Mountains]], the Some<U+015F> plateau and the Transylvanian plain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cluj.insse.ro/cmscluj/rw/pages/geogr.ro.do|title=Geografia jude<U+0163>ului Cluj|publisher=INSSE - Direc<U+0163>ia Regional<U+0103> de Statistic<U+0103> Cluj|accessdate=2008-03-15|language=Romanian}}</ref> It sprawls over the valleys of [[Some<U+015F>ul Mic]] and [[Nad<U+0103><U+015F> River (Some<U+015F>)|Nad<U+0103><U+015F>]], and, to some extent over the secondary valleys of the Pope<U+015F>ti, Chint<U+0103>u, Borhanci and Popii rivers.<ref name="geogr"/><ref name="hall-geography">{{cite web
|url=http://www.primariaclujnapoca.ro/docs/propiecte%20dezbateri/strategie/Anexa%2010%20-%20INFRASTRUCTURA.pdf|title=Amenajarea teritoriului, urbanism, infrastructur<U+0103>|accessdate=2008-03-12|publisher=Cluj-Napoca City Hall|language=Romanian|format=PDF |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080408202135/http://www.primariaclujnapoca.ro/docs/propiecte+dezbateri/strategie/Anexa+10+-+INFRASTRUCTURA.pdf |archivedate = April 8, 2008}}</ref> The southern part of the city occupies the upper terrace of the northern slope of [[Feleacu|Feleac]] Hill, and is surrounded on three sides by hills or mountains with heights between {{convert|500|m|ft}} and {{convert|700|m|ft}}.<ref name="hall-geography"/> The Some<U+015F> plateau is situated to the east, while the northern part of town includes ''Dealurile Clujului'' ("the Hills of Cluj"), with the peaks, Lombului (684&nbsp;m), Dealul Melcului (617&nbsp;m), Techint<U+0103>u (633&nbsp;m), Hoia (506&nbsp;m) and G<U+00E2>rb<U+0103>u (570&nbsp;m).<ref name="geogr"/> Other hills are located in the western districts, and the hills of Calvaria and [[Cet<U+0103><U+0163>uia, Cluj-Napoca|Cet<U+0103><U+0163>uia]] (''Belvedere'') are located near the centre of city.

Built on the banks of Some<U+015F>ul Mic River, the city is also crossed over by brooks or streams such as ''P<U+00E2>r<U+00E2>ul <U+0162>iganilor'', ''P<U+00E2>r<U+00E2>ul Pope<U+015F>ti'', ''P<U+00E2>r<U+00E2>ul N<U+0103>d<U+0103><U+015F>el'', ''P<U+00E2>r<U+00E2>ul Chintenilor'', ''P<U+00E2>r<U+00E2>ul Beca<U+015F>'', ''P<U+00E2>r<U+00E2>ul Mur<U+0103>torii''; ''[[Canalul Morilor, Cluj-Napoca|Canalul Morilor]]'' runs through the centre of town.<ref name="geogr">Luk<U+00E1>cs 2005, pp.9-11</ref>

A wide variety of flora grow in the [[Cluj-Napoca Botanical Garden]]; some animals have also found refuge there. The city has a number of other parks, of which the largest is the [[Cluj-Napoca Central Park|Central Park]]. This park was founded during the 19th century and includes an artificial lake with an island, as well as the largest casino in the city, ''Chios''. Other notable parks in the city are the [[Iuliu Ha<U+0163>ieganu]] Park of the [[Babe<U+015F>-Bolyai University]], which features some sport facilities, the [[Bogdan Petriceicu Hasdeu|Ha<U+015F>deu]] Park, within the eponymous student housing district, the high-elevation Cet<U+0103><U+0163>uia, and the Opera Park, behind the building of the [[Cluj-Napoca Romanian Opera|Romanian Opera]].

=== Surroundings ===
[[File:Cheile Turzii (Turda Gorges).jpg|thumb|left|[[Turda Gorges]] (south-east of Cluj) seen from the west end]]
[[File:Reflexii asupra sinelui 1.JPG|thumb|250px|left|[[Bon<U+0163>ida B<U+00E1>nffy Castle|B<U+00E1>nffy Castle]] (north-east of Cluj) is currently being restored]]
[[File:Magyargyer<U+0151>monostori utcar<U+00E9>szlet.jpg|thumb|right|Typical rural houses in [[M<U+0103>n<U+0103>stireni]], west of Cluj.]]

The city is surrounded by forests and grasslands. Rare species of plants, such as [[Calypso orchid|Venus's slipper]] and [[Iris (plant)|iris]], are found in the two botanical reservations of Cluj-Napoca, ''[[Rezerva<U+0163>ia F<U+00E2>na<U+0163>ele Clujului|F<U+00E2>na<U+0163>ele Clujului]]'' and ''Rezerva<U+0163>ia Valea Morii'' ("Mill Valley Reservation").<ref>Anton et al. 1973, pp.40-1</ref> Animals such as boars, badgers, foxes, rabbits and squirrels live in nearby forest areas such as F<U+0103>get and Hoia. The latter forest hosts the Romulus Vuia ethnographical park, with exhibits dating back to 1678.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cjnet.ro/t/obiectur.html|title=Tourist Attractions|publisher=DNT Cluj|year=1999|accessdate=2008-03-15}}</ref> Various people report alien encounters in the Hoia-Baciu forest, large networks of [[catacomb]]s that connect the old churches of the city, or the presence of a monster in the nearby lake of [[Tarni<U+0163>a]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Tatar|first=Florentina|url=http://www.monitorulcj.ro/cms/site/m_cj/news/clujul_subteran_30348.html|title=Clujul subteran|date=2008-01-08|accessdate=2008-03-14|publisher=Monitorul de Cluj|language=Romanian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=C<U+00E2>mpan|first=Leti<U+0163>ia|url=http://www.clujeanul.ro/cluj/miturile-clujului-2445452|title=Miturile Clujului|publisher=Clujeanul|date=2008-03-11|accessdate=2008-03-14|language=Romanian}}</ref>

A modern, {{convert|750|m|yd|adj=on}}-long [[ski resort]] is sits on Feleac Hill, with an altitude difference of {{convert|98|m|yd}} between its highest and lowest points. This ski resort offers outdoor lighting, [[artificial snow]] and a [[ski tow]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realitatea.net/partia-feleac-de-langa-cluj-a-fost-inaugurata-sambata_127626.html|title=P<U+00E2>rtia Feleac, de l<U+00E2>ng<U+0103> Cluj, a fost inaugurat<U+0103> s<U+00E2>mb<U+0103>t<U+0103>|publisher=Realitatea.net|date=2007-12-23|accessdate=2008-03-12|language=Romanian}}</ref> [[B<U+0103>i<U+015F>oara]] [[winter resort]] is located approximately {{convert|50|km|mi}} from the city of Cluj-Napoca, and includes two ski trails, for beginner and advanced skiers, respectively: ''Zidul Mic'' and ''Zidul Mare''.<ref name="andras">Andr<U+00E1>s et al. 2003, p.81</ref> Two other summer resorts/spas are included in the metropolitan area, namely [[Cojocna]] and [[Some<U+015F>eni]] Baths.<ref>Andr<U+00E1>s et al. 2003, p.131</ref>

There are a large number of castles in the countryside surroundings, constructed by wealthy medieval families living in the city. The most notable of them is the [[Bon<U+0163>ida B<U+00E1>nffy Castle]]<U+2014>once known as "the [[Palace of Versailles|Versailles]] of Transylvania"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heritagetraining-banffycastle.org/index.php?p=21|title=Cultural tourism|quote=Formerly known as the Transylvanian Versailles, B<U+00E1>nffy castle, Bontida is one of the most beautiful historic buildings in the Carpathian basin.|publisher=Transilvania Trust|accessdate=2008-03-14}}</ref><U+2014>in the nearby village of [[Bon<U+0163>ida]], {{convert|32|km|mi}} from the city centre. In 1963, the castle was used as a set for [[Liviu Ciulei]]'s film ''[[Forest of the Hanged]]'', which won an award at [[Cannes Film Festival|Cannes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cronicaromana.ro/index.php?art=78552|first=Cornel|last=Enache|title=Castelele Romaniei (II)|publisher=Cronica Rom<U+00E2>n<U+0103>|accessdate=2008-03-16|language=Romanian}}</ref> There are other castles located in the vicinity of the city; indeed, the castle at Bon<U+0163>ida is not even the only one constructed by the B<U+00E1>nffy family. The commune of [[Gil<U+0103>u, Cluj|Gil<U+0103>u]] features the Wass-B<U+00E1>nffy Castle,<ref>Andr<U+00E1>s et al. 2003, p.153</ref> while another B<U+00E1>nffy Castle is located in the [[R<U+0103>scruci, Cluj|R<U+0103>scruci]] area.<ref>Andr<U+00E1>s et al. 2003, p.92</ref> In addition, [[Nicula]] Monastery, erected during the 18th century, is an important pilgrimage site in northern Transylvania. This monastery houses the renowned wonder-working [[Madonna (art)|Madonna]] of Nicula.<ref name="sfantamaria">Andr<U+00E1>s et al. 2003, p.142</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gardianul.ro/2007/08/15/actualitate-c24/romanii_sarbatoresc_adormirea_maicii_domnului_si_ziua_marinei-s99513.html|title=Rom<U+00E2>nii s<U+0103>rb<U+0103>toresc Adormirea Maicii Domnului <U+015F>i Ziua Marinei|publisher=Gardianul|accessdate=2008-03-14|language=Romanian|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080222092950/http://www.gardianul.ro/2007/08/15/actualitate-c24/romanii_sarbatoresc_adormirea_maicii_domnului_si_ziua_marinei-s99513.html |archivedate = February 22, 2008|deadurl=yes}}</ref> The [[icon]] is said to have wept between February 15 and March 12, 1669.<ref name="Nicula">{{cite web|url=http://www.ici.ro/romania/en/turism/m_nicula.html|title=A monastery attracts thousands of Christians|accessdate=2008-03-12|publisher=National Institute for Research and Development in Informatics|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080307154643/http://www.ici.ro/romania/en/turism/m_nicula.html |archivedate = March 7, 2008|deadurl=yes}}</ref> During this time, nobles, officers, laity and clergy came to see it. At first they were sceptical, looking at it on both sides, but then humbly crossed themselves and returned home petrified by the wonder they had seen.<ref name="Nicula"/> During the feast of the [[Dormition of the Theotokos]] (commemorating the death of the [[Mary (mother of Jesus)|Virgin Mary]]) on August 15, more than 150,000 people from all over the country come to visit the monastery.<ref name="sfantamaria"/>

=== Climate ===

Cluj-Napoca has a [[continental climate]], characterised by warm dry summers and cold winters. The climate is influenced by the city's proximity to the [[Apuseni Mountains]], as well as by [[urbanisation]]. Some West-Atlantic influences are present during winter and autumn. Winter temperatures are often below {{convert|0|C|F|0}}, even though they rarely drop below {{convert|-10|C|F|0}}. On average, snow covers the ground for 65 days each winter.<ref>{{cite web
|url=http://www.primariaclujnapoca.ro/proiecte-dezbateri/Politici_comunitare_de_mediu.pdf|title=Mediu: Cluj-Napoca|accessdate=2008-03-21|publisher=Prim<U+0103>ria Cluj-Napoca|language=Romanian|format=PDF |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070125155551/http://www.primariaclujnapoca.ro/proiecte-dezbateri/Politici_comunitare_de_mediu.pdf |archivedate = January 25, 2007}}</ref> In summer, the average temperature is approximately {{convert|18|C|F|0}} (the average for July and August), despite the fact that temperatures sometimes reach {{convert|35|C|F|0}} to {{convert|40|C|F|0}} in mid-summer in the city centre. Although average [[Precipitation (meteorology)|precipitation]] and [[humidity]] during summer is low, there are infrequent yet heavy and often violent storms. During spring and autumn, temperatures vary between {{convert|13|C|F|0}} to {{convert|18|C|F|0}}, and precipitation during this time tends to be higher than in summer, with more frequent yet milder periods of rain.

