== Law and government ==

=== Administration ===
[[File:Primaria Cluj-Napoca1.jpg|thumb|[[Cluj-Napoca City Hall]]]]
[[File:CL Cluj-Napoca 2012-2016.png|thumb|Local council composition [[Romanian local election, 2012|2012 election]]:<br />
{{legend|#ffffff|[[Social Liberal Union]] (12)}}
{{legend|#ff9900|[[Democratic Liberal Party (Romania)|Democratic Liberal Party]] (10)}}
{{legend|#75ab17|[[Democratic Union of Hungarians in Romania]] (4)}}
{{legend|#800080|[[People's Party - Dan Diaconescu]] (1)}}]]

[[File:Cluj-Napoca Districts.jpg|thumb|Map of Cluj-Napoca's districts (2007)]]

{{Main|Politics of Cluj-Napoca}}
{{See also|Cluj-Napoca metropolitan area}}

The city government is headed by a [[List of mayors of Cluj-Napoca|mayor]].<ref name="law-admin">{{cite web
|url=http://www.cdep.ro/pls/legis/legis_pck.htp_act_text?idt=27123|title=Law no. 215 / 21 April 2001: Legea administra<U+0163>iei publice locale|accessdate=2008-03-12|publisher=Parliament of Romania|language=Romanian}}</ref> Since 2012, the office is held by [[Emil Boc]], who was returned at that year's [[Romanian local election, 2012|local election]] for a third term, having resigned in 2008 to become [[Prime Minister of Romania|Prime Minister]].<ref name="juramant"/> Decisions are approved and discussed by the [[Local government|local council]] (''consiliu local'') made up of 27 elected councillors.<ref name="law-admin"/> The city is divided into 15 districts (''cartiere'') laid out radially. City hall intends to develop local administrative branches for most of the districts.

